commitResults.messageTitle: Rename, add greeting and exit message
commitResults.messageBody:
- renamed bot to "RoTodo"
- added greeting on running and exit message

- RoTodo echoes input back to user
- RoTodo exits program when receiving "bye" input

- user inputs are added as task
- "list" input will print out tasklist

commitResults.messageTitle: Add "mark as done" and 3 task subtypes
commitResults.messageBody: - Task subclasses added: ToDos, Events, Deadlines

- Refactor code
   - move user input processing out of tasklist class into main CLI
     class (RoTodo)
   - organize codebase into packages:
      - rotodo.tasklist
      - rotodo.exception
- RoTodo can validate user input and outputs error message accordingly
   - custom exceptions added: InvalidInputException,
     IncompleteInputException

commitResults.messageTitle: Add save and load data feature
commitResults.messageBody:
RoTodo now loads data on startup and saves data if properly exited.

Refactor:
- RoTodo main class refactored into Parser, Storage and Ui to handle
  individual processes.
- saveString functions added to Tasks to format string for data saving.
- saveList function added to TaskList to facilitate data saving.

Todo:
- Modify text-ui-test to test load/save feature

User input date/time is parsed into LocalDateTime format, but requires a
strict date/time format (dd/MM/yyyy HHmm).

Processes performed are not clearly segregated between Parser, TaskList
and Ui.

Commands that should be performed in the same scope is being performed
by different classes, affecting code readability.

Abstracting user commands into individual classes allow for better code
readability, and allow the processes to run in the same scope.

Let's define Command classes, that can be execute() to perform the
command as required.
